Operating Range
Estimated usable sensor range:
Minimum reliable detection: ~60 dB
Maximum tested level: ~95–100 dB
Below 60 dB, measurements become inconsistent.
Above 90 dB, the sensor begins to overestimate sound levels.
Key Findings
1. Linear region
The sensor performs best between:
65 dB – 85 dB
Errors in this region remain relatively small.
2. Low-level instability
Below 60 dB, RMS output fluctuates and cannot reliably represent sound level.
3. High-level overestimation
Above 90 dB, the sensor increasingly overestimates actual sound levels.
4. Calibration effectiveness
Using 70 dB → RMS = 1 provides a reasonable calibration reference for mid-range measurements.
Conclusion
The tested sound sensor provides reliable measurements within the approximate range:
60 dB – 90 dB
Within this region, measurement error remains relatively low. Outside this range, the sensor exhibits:
Reduced stability at low sound levels
Increasing error at high sound levels
Future improvements could include:
Multi-point calibration
Noise filtering
Sensor linearization
